/*
https://leetcode.com/problems/best-time-to-buy-and-sell-stock-ii/description/

You are given an integer array prices where prices[i] is the price of a given stock on the ith day.

On each day, you may decide to buy and/or sell the stock. You can only hold at most one share of the stock at any time. However, you can buy it then immediately sell it on the same day.

Find and return the maximum profit you can achieve.

 

Example 1:

Input: prices = [7,1,5,3,6,4]
Output: 7
Explanation: Buy on day 2 (price = 1) and sell on day 3 (price = 5), profit = 5-1 = 4.
Then buy on day 4 (price = 3) and sell on day 5 (price = 6), profit = 6-3 = 3.
Total profit is 4 + 3 = 7.
Example 2:

Input: prices = [1,2,3,4,5]
Output: 4
Explanation: Buy on day 1 (price = 1) and sell on day 5 (price = 5), profit = 5-1 = 4.
Total profit is 4.
Example 3:

Input: prices = [7,6,4,3,1]
Output: 0
Explanation: There is no way to make a positive profit, so we never buy the stock to achieve the maximum profit of 0.
 

Constraints:

1 <= prices.length <= 3 * 104
0 <= prices[i] <= 104

*/

 /*

> On each day, you may decide to buy and/or sell the stock.
> You can only hold at most one share at any time.
> However, you **can buy it then immediately sell it on the same day**.

---

## 🔑 Key Clarification:

The problem **doesn't require** you to **buy on one day and sell on the next** specifically.
Instead, it allows you to:

* Buy and **immediately sell on the same day** (i.e., `prices[i] > prices[i]` is allowed),
* Or hold the stock and sell **on any future day** when profitable.

---

## ✅ Why Greedy Works

In this specific version (often called **Stock II**), the reason we **accumulate profits where `prices[i] > prices[i-1]`** is that:

* It **captures every small uptrend**.
* You **simulate buying at `i-1` and selling at `i`**, which is equivalent (in net profit) to buying at the valley and selling at the peak.

This is mathematically the same as:

```
Buy at local minima, sell at local maxima.
```

But summing all `positive differences` is simpler and gives the same result.

---

## 🧠 Important Distinction

| Variant                         | Constraint              | Strategy                  |
| ------------------------------- | ----------------------- | ------------------------- |
| **Stock I**                     | Buy and sell only once  | Track global min and max  |
| **Stock II (This one)**         | Buy/sell multiple times | Greedily sum all uptrends |
| **Stock III/IV**                | Max 2 or k transactions | DP needed                 |
| **Stock with cooldown or fees** | Additional constraints  | Advanced DP               |

    */

    public int maxProfit(int[] prices) {
        int maxProfit=0;
        for(int i=1; i<prices.length; i++){
            if(prices[i]>prices[i-1]){
                maxProfit+=prices[i]-prices[i-1];
            }

        }
        return maxProfit;
    }
